    %article#lat-den-ratte-komma-in-2008
      %hgroup
        %h2{:lang => "sw"} Låt den rätte komma in
        %h3 Swedish, "Let the Right One In"
      %p.metadata
        A 2008 romantic horror film directed by Tomas Alfredson.
        %a{:href => "http://www.imdb.com/title/tt1139797/", :title => "Låt den rätte komma in (2008) on IMDb"} IMDb
        %a{:href => "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Let_the_Right_One_In_(film)", :title => "Let the Right One In (film) on Wikipedia"} Wikipedia
      %figure
        %img{:alt => "Screencap of Eli who is trying to solve the Rubik's cube. The shot is made of only the hands and the Rubik's cube.", :src => "images/rubiks-cube-lat-den-ratte-komma-in.jpg"}
          %figcaption
            Eli is trying to solve the Rubik's cube.
            %small Copyright EFTI, 2008
      %section.appearance
        %h3 Appearance
        %p There are three scenes where the Rubik's Cube appears.
        %ol
          %li
            The first is when a girl named Eli
            %small (Lina Leandersson)
            looks at Oskar
            %small (Kåre Hedebrant)
            trying to solve the cube. She asks about it, and Oskar lends her the cube. In the scene is visible that Oskar is only able to solve one side of the cube.
          %li In a scene without spoken words, Oskar finds the cube on the spot where he met Eli earlier. The cube is solved.
          %li
            In a later scene, Oskar asks Eli how she solved the cube. She states that she
            %q just twisted it
            and starts explaining how she solved the cube, before the scene ends.
      %section.comments
        %h3 Comments
        %ul
          %li The explained method is a corners-first method. This is usually not a method beginners practice.
      %section.transcript
        %h3 Transcript
        %dl
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd What's that?
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd This? It's a Rubik's Cube.
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd Is it some kind of puzzle?
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd Yeah… Want to try? You can give it back tomorrow.
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd I might not be here tomorrow.
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd
            The day after, then. But that's it.
            %small Oskar hands over the cube to Eli.
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd How do you do it?
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd You want each side to be a solid color. Like this…
        %figure.small
          %img{:alt => "Screencap of Oskar with a solved Rubik's cube in his hand. There is a certain amount of snow on top of the cube, since it is winter.", :src => "images/rubiks-cube-small-lat-den-ratte-komma-in.jpg"}
            %figcaption
              Oskar finds the Rubik's cube.
              %small Copyright EFTI, 2008
        %aside
          %p The scene ends. In a later scene Oskar finds the solved cube. In an even later scene this happens:
        %dl
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd How did you do it?
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd I just twisted it.
        %aside
          %p (…)
        %dl
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd Then you don't get any birthday presents, do you?
          %dt.s Eli
          %dd No.
          %dt.p Oskar
          %dd You can have this if you want.
